05807nam a22007335i 9780889209077DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892090777 a10.51644/97808892090772doi  a(DE-B1597)667799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN56.A89bT73 2005eb 7aPSY0100002bisacsh04a809.935922221 aKadar, Marlene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTracing the Autobiographical /cMarlene Kadar, Susanna Egan; ed. by Linda Warley, Jeanne Perreault. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife Writing00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTracing The Autobiographical: Unlikelydocuments, Unexpected Places -- tKatie.Com: My Story -- tReading The Autobiographical In Personal Home Pages -- tReality Tv Has Spoken -- tPerforming The Auto/Biographical Pact -- tDomestic Space And The Idea Of Home In Auto/Biographical Practices -- tThe Shifting Grounds Of Exile And Home In Daphne Marlatt's Steveston' -- tLaw Stories As Life Stories -- tMuriel Rukeyser -- tGender, Nation, And Self-Narration -- tGiving Pain A Place In The World -- tCircular Journeys And Glass Bridges -- tThe Devouring -- tThe Authors And Their Essays -- tAcknowledgments -- tWorks Cited -- tBooks in the Life Writing Series Published0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in Tracing the Autobiographical work with the literatures of several nations to reveal the intersections of broad agendas (for example, national ones) with the personal, the private, and the individual. Attending to ethics, exile, tyranny, and hope, the contributors listen for echoes and murmurs as well as authoritative declarations. They also watch for the appearance of auto/biography in unexpected places, tracing patterns from materials that have been left behind. Many of the essays return to the question of text or traces of text, demonstrating that the language of autobiography, as well as the textualized identities of individual persons, can be traced in multiple media and sometimes unlikely documents, each of which requires close textual examination. These “unlikely documents” include a deportation list, an art exhibit, reality TV, Web sites and chat rooms, architectural spaces, and government memos, as well as the more familiar literary genres—a play, the long poem, or the short story. Interdisciplinary in scope and contemporary in outlook, Tracing the Autobiographical is a welcome addition to autobiography scholarship, focusing on non-traditional genres and on the importance of location and place in life writing. Read the chapter “Gender, Nation, and Self-Narration: Three Generations of Dayan Women in Palestine/Israel” by Bina Freiwald on the Concordia University Library Spectrum Research Repository website.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiography in literature. 0aAutobiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Psychotherapy / Counseling.2bisacsh1 aBuss, Helen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowe, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Susanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreiwald, Bina Toledo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrace, Sherrill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelms, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadar, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKertzer, Adrienne, ec